Yes, for fast migration(kubernetes) we are using aws ebs with disk type gp2. The iops calculation formula is 3 * GB. The minimum iops is 3000 and the maximum is 16000. 
iops is indeed a problem, but this was not the case before with levelDB. I am curious what advantages does pebbleDB have over levelDB? Does it reduce latency, we deploy a lot of staking operations and often the balance is reduced due to slow synchronization
@karalabe

> That would be awesome if it actually protected against unclean shutdowns.

@Tadouh if that is your primary pain-point, then you should run with `gcmode=archive`. That way, geth doesn't keep as much in memory, and is not as dependent on an orderly shutdown. 

The price to pay is that more 'junk' is accumulated over time, but it should give less problems due to unclean shutdowns.

> Not trying to complain about it, just wondering why we dont use a database like prysm use

> So, something matters, i am not sure if it the database cause bolt handles it perfectly, 

> I am certainly not tech savvy like you dev

@Tadouh we are telling you facts. It does not matter what the backend is. We are not persisting to disk, we are maintaining data in memory, in order to do pruning. If we crash in that time, we need to recover that, it takes hours. Regardless of what data-backend we did not write to. 


> An archive node is 13TB, have fun

@karalabe come on, it isn't, there's no need to do archive _from genesis_. It just grows faster.
